From: s9ubxt@almserv.uucp (Ben Taylor)
Subject: Re: olvwm for linux?
Date: Mon, 22 Nov 1993 23:02:20 GMT

terryd@extro.ucc.su.OZ.AU (Terry Dawson) writes:
>clark@ist.flinders.edu.au (Steven R Clark) writes:
>>In article 30i@news.ysu.edu, ai539@yfn.ysu.edu (Kent Fox) writes:
>>>
>>>Has anyone recompiled olvwm for a modern linux kernel/gcc/XFree86?
>>>I'm having problems in slave.c ... and can't seem to trackdown 
>>>getrlimit() or  RLIMIT_NOFILE.  Any help would be appreciated.
>>>
>>>                               Pat Eyler
>>>                              pate@cpu.us.dynix.com

RLIMIT_NOFILE is a parameter in the SunOS include file sys/resource.h
which is currently value 6.  It is used in calling {get/set}rlimit
to get or set the current value for number of open files per process
currently allowed.  

In linux sys/resource.h, it includes linux/resource.h.  In linux/resource.h
there is a parameter RLIMIT_OFILE which has a value of 8.  The function
getrlimit is defined in sys/resource.h.  From the asm source in kernel/sys.c
it looks like this is what I would expect to see.  What you should be able
to do is define RLIMIT_OFILE=RLIMIT_NOFILE.  I don't have the source for
olvwm so I don't know exactly what should be the correct fix for Linux.
However, from what I can tell, this should fix your problem.

If anyone has anything to add, I'll listen.

>>My effort bombed out before that, still tracking down the problem. If you get the
>>thing to compile, perhaps you could put it on sunsite (some hints in a text file on
>>how you got it to compile might be a good idea too - I'd be interested anyway)

>Try including <sys/param.h> and changing RLIMIT_NOFILE to NOFILE.
>Oh, and use -DSYSV in the CFLAGS.
>I assumed it was just a definei for the maximum number of files
>that could be opened, I didn't check real hard, but I've used
>the binary that I compiled as a result for months without a problem.

>Terry
>-- 
>--- Terry Dawson, terryd@extro.ucc.su.oz.au

I first mailed this to Terry cause I was a bit confused about his solution.
He indicated this might be a FAQ?  If so, who needs what?

Ben

Ben Taylor
s9ubxt@fnma.com

