From: Frank.Peters@MsState.Edu (Frank Peters)
Crossposted-To: comp.infosystems.www,comp.windows.x,comp.windows.x.i386unix,comp.windows.x.motif,gnu.misc.discuss,comp.sources.d
Subject: Re: Don't use Motif for free sw: it now requires runtime royalties!
Date: 22 Nov 1993 19:07:12 -0600
Reply-To: fwp@CC.MsState.Edu

In article <CGwMu8.DHH@dvorak.amd.com>
        aad@dvorak.amd.com (Anthony A. Datri) says:
>>(a) Our academic site license lets us distribute free,
>>    statically-linked binaries
>
>Read my lips:  binaries -- especially statically-linked ones -- don't cut it.

I'm not quite sure what to make of this.  It cuts if for most of the
major software vendors in the world.  The only real difference between
NCSA and Frame or Interleaf or SAS is that NCSA doesn't charge you any
money.

And it seems to cut it for Mosaic in particular.  At least, it seems to
have managed to be quite popular in spite of this limitation.

>>(b) EVERY significant workstation vendor has committed to Motif
>
>Even if it were true, so what?

So they can count on a significant number of their user base being able
to download the thing and run it with no modifications.

>>    standard on Unix workstations.  (Athena does *not* count
>
>Why, because it's available and does the job without undue resource hogging?

Because its ugly and lacks widget features that Mosaic almost certainly
makes heavy use of (the "ugly" is subjective of course).

>
>>    Mosaic too seriously to base it on anything not directly supported
>>    by the majority of hw/sw vendors out there.
>
>shipped != supported.

This is just as true for Athena, Tk and /bin/sh for that matter.

>>    No, Motif isn't free,
>
>The real point is that it isn't affordable.  Binary-only releases have too
>many shortcomings, and the O$F makes the source unreasonably expensive.

I'm not much of a fan of Motif (I prefer the looks of Open Look and the
XView toolkit personally) but Motif is almost certainly the wave of the
future.  As more and more of the commercial workstation vendors (who
make up the lions share of the market despite the popularity of linux)
ship a Motif environment as their default user environment more and
more applications writers (commercial and freeware) will begin using
it.

Efforts would be much better spent getting a motif-clone project going
(GNU leitmotif?) than beating on NCSA for using a popular toolkit that
they like to develop software that they aren't charging you for or even
forcing you to use.

