From: johnsonm@calypso.oit.unc.edu (Michael K. Johnson)
Subject: Re: Some ideas and reasons for a more modular kernel.
Date: 23 Nov 1993 01:29:03 GMT


In article <1993Nov22.085300.1153@kth.se> md85-epi@hemul.nada.kth.se (Urban Koistinen) writes:

   [ about the LDM ]
   Will it be done this month?

It would have stood a chance of an initial implementation if I hadn't
gotten a new job earlier than I bargained for... :-)  Now the LDM may
not come out until after version 1.0, which might not be so bad anyway.

   Another use would be encryption.

Yep.  That's the beauty of the scheme.  You can tack in just about
anything you can think of that a driver-driver could do.

   Encrypted swap anyone?

;-)

   While I think this is good for a RW file system, inode and other
   metadata could be stored compressed on a read-only file system.

Is metadata really very compressible?  I suppose that there are a lot
of zeros in inodes, but inodes are relatively small, and would still
be on different blocks, and you might loose as much space overhead to
storing the compressed inodes as you gained from compressing them.  I
can't say without real data, but until someone shows me numbers, I
reserve the right to remain skeptical...

michaelkjohnson

