Crossposted-To: comp.windows.x,comp.windows.x.i386unix,comp.windows.x.motif,gnu.misc.discuss,comp.sources.d
From: muts@compi.hobby.nl (Peter Mutsaers)
Subject: Re: Don't use Motif for free sw: it now requires runtime royalties!
Date: Sun, 21 Nov 1993 09:54:33 GMT

>> On 19 Nov 1993 07:13:46 GMT, bernhard@trick.ani.univie.ac.at
>> (Bernhard Strassl) said:

  BS> As it seems that Motif will be the dominating GUI on Un*x/X systems in
  BS> the near future, I think that the 'boring and long task' is worth to be
  BS> done.

  BS> Consider you have written a nice application or some reuseable
  BS> parts for commercial purposes (using the evil Motif). Now you
  BS> want to use it at home on your Linux system - if everything is
  BS> different there you can forget this!  You would have to rewrite
  BS> everything, even without being able to reuse your programming
  BS> expierience.

Better yet, lets make sure that Motif will not dominate the GUI. What
customers want is a Motif *look and feel*, they don't care how it is
implemented.

For several commercial projects I used Tcl/Tk instead of Motif. The
customer was happy with it because it looked as it should.

They were surprised when I told them it was made with use of a public
domain GUI package. But more and more also the commercial world
recognizes that there is very valueable and high quality public
domain software, and at least those I worked for were quite
enthousiastic about it because it meant they could run the software I
made not only on workstations that had already Motif installed, but on
any other too.
