From: becker@super.org (Donald J. Becker)
Subject: Re: [Q]: I want to develop EISA Ethernet driver HOWTO ?
Date: Mon, 22 Nov 1993 16:11:22 GMT

In article <2cqgv4$8gn@bambi.zdv.uni-mainz.de>,
PC-Gruppe <pcgruppe@n1.imsd.uni-mainz.de> wrote:
>I am still using Longshine EISA Ethernet Cards with WFW. The Card s are  
>fast and nice. I want t to use this cards also with LINUX and there is  
>manpower to develop a driver, BUT i dont know how to write a driver for  
>LINUX. I get everything i need from longshine, like information about the  
>chipset used, its registers, SCO Driver sources, some Assembler code ... .
>Please help me and LINUX will get EISA ethernet power. There is no  
>planning for commercial use of this so it will be released from the first  
>beta version.

First of all, people shouldn't lust after "EISA ethernet power", at least
until they start running 100base*.  A bus-master AMD PCnet/ISA LANCE board
should usually outperform a slave EISA ethercard.

Secondly, Linux is already getting "EISA ethernet power".  I've written a
driver and been working with glee@ardnassak.math.clemson.edu to get the Ansel
AC3200 working.  Earlier I worked with Aaron Monfils, aaron@aaron.cps.edu, to
get the EISA version of the 3c509 working.

But you are well on your way: you've already gotten documentation, and that
can sometimes be the hardest part.  If you'll mail the basic information I'll
look over it and give you an estimate on how long it will to write a driver.
I've even been known to stay awake until the driver is written, but I won't
promise service like that.


Donald Becker                                          becker@super.org
IDA Supercomputing Research Center
17100 Science Drive, Bowie MD 20715                        301-805-7482

